  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. A normalized wave function can have absolute psi squared equal to two at its peak. Probabilities cannot exceed one, so has quantum mechanics contradicted itself?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "How can |psi(x)|^2 be greater than one while every measurable probability remains between zero and one?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — THE BORN RULE",
            "segment": "Density Is Not Probability",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "checking units and integrating area…",
            "output": [
              "|psi|^2 is probability per unit length.",
              "Interval probability is the area under the density."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.29,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "For a continuous position, absolute psi squared is a probability density, not a dimensionless probability at one exact point.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "separate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.87,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "In one dimension its units are inverse length. A value of two per nanometer is not the number two as a probability.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "label"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.21,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The probability for an interval is the integral of the density across that interval: an area, with the length units cancelling.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.02,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Consider psi equals one over square root a times e to the minus absolute x over a. It is normalized on the whole line.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.64,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Its density is one over a times e to the minus two absolute x over a. With a equal to 0.5 nanometers, the peak is two per nanometer.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "calculate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.98,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Now ask for the particle within plus or minus 0.1 nanometers. The exact area is one minus e to the minus 0.4, about 0.330.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "shade"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.26,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "The peak density exceeds one, yet the highlighted interval probability is safely below one. There is no contradiction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.27,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "For an ideal continuous variable, the probability of one exact point is zero. A finite detector always covers a nonzero interval or volume.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "zoom"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.43,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The density's numerical height also changes when you change units. Two per nanometer is two billion per meter, while every integrated probability stays unchanged.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "convert"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Population density works the same way. Ten thousand people per square kilometer is far above one; only density times area gives a count.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "analogy"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.64,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "Never ask whether a continuous density is below one. Check its units, then integrate the region your measurement actually resolves.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.79,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:48:18"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. A nearly constant density is three per nanometer across a 0.2 nanometer bin. Estimate the probability in that bin.",
